*Default:* enabled

~~~lua
ionide={
  IonideNvimSettings={
    ---defaults to true 
    AutomaticWorkspaceInit = false,
  },
},
~~~

##### Enable/disable signature help on cursor move

*Default:* disabled

~~~lua
ionide={
  IonideNvimSettings={
    ShowSignatureOnCursorMove = true,
  },
}
~~~

##### Use Ionide's richer formatted documentation for `K`

*Default:* disabled

When enabled, Ionide sets a buffer-local `K` mapping on F#/FSAC attach that:

- starts with `fsharp/documentation`
- enriches with `fsharp/documentationSymbol` when FSAC exposes a documentation target
- includes diagnostics for the current line
- falls back to normal `vim.lsp.buf.hover()` when needed

This is useful because the default hover often shows the same style of payload the VS Code integration uses,
including a "go look over there" style documentation link. The Ionide documentation hover instead tries to fetch
the richer documentation payload directly and display it in Neovim.

The effective resolution order is:

1. `fsharp/documentation`
2. standard `textDocument/hover` only to discover the documentation target metadata
3. `fsharp/documentationSymbol` when that metadata is available
4. append diagnostics for the current line
5. fallback to `vim.lsp.buf.hover()`

So the goal is not merely "show hover", but "show the actual useful docs first, then include the local diagnostic context."

~~~lua
ionide={
  IonideNvimSettings={
    UseIonideDocumentationHover = true,
  },
}
~~~

##### Recommended LazyVim setup

If you're using LazyVim and configuring FsAutoComplete like this:

~~~lua
fsautocomplete = require("ionide").setup({
  IonideNvimSettings = {
    UseIonideDocumentationHover = true,
  },
})
~~~

then a good division of labor is:

- let LazyVim keep owning generic LSP keymaps, inlay hints, and folds
- let Ionide own FsAutoComplete-specific commands, notifications, project/workspace actions, and richer F# docs hover

That avoids duplicated attach-time behavior while still giving F# a better-than-default hover experience.

##### Set the deep level of directory hierarchy when searching for sln/fsprojs

*Default:* `4'

~~~lua
ionide={
  settings={
    FSharp={
      workspaceModePeekDeepLevel = 4,
    },
  },
}
~~~

##### Ignore specific directories when loading a workspace

*Default:* empty

~~~lua
ionide={
  settings={
    FSharp={
      excludeProjectDirectories = { "paket-files", ".fable", "packages", "node_modules" },
    },
  },
}
~~~


#### Linter & Formatter Settings

Linting and formatting are powered by [FSharpLint](https://github.com/fsprojects/FSharpLint) and [Fantomas](https://github.com/fsprojects/fantomas/) respectively. Both use their own configuration files. See their docs: [FSharpLint](http://fsprojects.github.io/FSharpLint/#Configuration-Files) and [Fantomas](https://github.com/fsprojects/fantomas/blob/master/docs/Documentation.md#--config-path-to-file-or-folder).

#### Syntax Highlighting

Ionide-Nvim includes basic Vim syntax highlighting for F# (`syntax/fsharp.vim`). For modern, accurate highlighting, use [Tree-sitter](https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter) with the F# grammar:

~~~lua
-- In your nvim-treesitter config:
require("nvim-treesitter.configs").setup({
  ensure_installed = { "fsharp" },
})
~~~

